However, it's crucial to manage expectations and avoid comparing the food here to the offerings in San Gabriel Valley or Little Saigon area. -1 star for the pricing, but considering the prime location and convenience, it's understandable. Quick tip: You can find Downtown LA Pho inside the City National Plaza's food court, located on the bottom floor of the plaza.", 'languageCode': 'en'}, 'originalText': {'text': "Downtown LA Pho stands out as the perfect spot if you crave authentic Vietnamese Pho right in the heart of the financial district of DTLA. The pho and soup base boast delightful flavors. The staff is exceptionally friendly, providing great service, and the portion sizes are satisfying. Service was friendly, although at one point it was difficult to get their attention to refill our hot green tea. They didn't rush us at all, unlike many other places (taking order, giving you the food, ask how's everything, once they saw you're on the last bite, here is your bill.) The body and hair products provided were wonderful and luxurious, but since the bathroom had zero ventilation, my towels remained wet even after 24 hours. reviews:
[{'name': 'places/ChIJO0XoWZjHwoARcnkNKTFjpG4/reviews/ChdDSUhNMG9nS0VJQ0FnTUNRMzlxLXZnRRAB', 'relativePublishTimeDescription': '2 months ago', 'rating': 5, 'text': {'text': 'Prepare to be seduced by the simmering symphony of flavors at Shabuya, a hot pot haven that transcends the typical dining experience. Stepping inside is like entering a warm embrace, the expansive space effortlessly accommodating both intimate tête-à-têtes and boisterous gatherings. The air is thick with anticipation, a gentle hum of contented chatter mingling with the tantalizing aroma of simmering broths.

Let's talk about the heart of the matter: the broth. Shabuya doesn't just offer broth; they deliver an elixir of pure deliciousness. I opted for the Shabuya broth, and from the first spoonful, I was transported. It was a revelation, a depth of flavor that spoke of hours, perhaps days, of patient simmering. Each nuanced note unfolded on my palate, a testament to culinary artistry. This wasn't just soup; it was a soul-warming potion.

The buffet is a treasure trove of culinary delightful ingredients with a sauce bar to enhance your hot pot broth. In addition you have five selected meats of your choice, each promising tender succulence, and a vibrant array of fresh ingredients beckoned. The freedom to customize my hot pot was exhilarating. With five distinct broth options, the possibilities were endless.

The ambiance is effortlessly chic, a perfect backdrop for any occasion. The attentive staff, a well-coordinated team, ensured every need was met with a smile. And those individual table burners? A stroke of genius, maintaining the perfect temperature for our bubbling cauldron of goodness.

To complement our culinary adventure, we indulged in Sapporo Premium beer. Its smooth, non-bitter finish was the perfect counterpoint to the rich, savory broth. A truly refined brew.

Despite the alluring "all-you-can-eat" promise, I found myself gloriously defeated after just one round. The sheer abundance and quality of the ingredients were overwhelming in the best possible way. Shabuya isn't just a meal; it's an experience, a journey into the heart of flavor. If you're seeking a hot pot adventure that will leave you utterly satisfied, look no further. Shabuya is where culinary dreams come to life, one simmering, flavorful spoonful at a time.

Be sure to sign up for the wait-list. It will help knowing where you are in the queue of others. Be prepared to pay for a meal that starts at $34.99 just to be rushed out the door.

It's a NO from ME... I must be on a roll because this is the second time I come to a place that serves noodles and they're either bland and/or the broth is very underwhelming.

I tried the miso and pork broth, neither of them did it for me. The point of broth is to make it flavorful, not basic. It sucks when the best items here are the gyoza and meats. I loved the ribeye and wagyu round, it's too bad you have to pair it with their lame broth. This time the noodles were slightly better than my last visit but I'm still very disappointed.

Shabuya is a restaurant for hot pot beginners. Thankfully, the hot pot procedure is fairly straightforward but some of the cookers are extremely hot while others are hardly working! It's so annoying to have boiling hot broth or cold broth. Also, the staff is very slow to refill your broth or have attitude when you ask them for a refill. I encountered a dude who was very unprofessional with me and was staring me down.

I'm also a bit disappointed in the outside decor, usually I don't judge a place in that department but it's so sad out in their little greenery section that I have to mention it. There's spaces for outdoor dining and they're completely neglected, it looks surreal and dirty. Also, there's an area for a pond, it's totally dry! The inside is beautifully done with a classy cozy interior. Second, the staff were super friendly—-probably helped since relatively no one was inside but still nice attitudes all around.

The reason for the bad rating is mainly because of the way they operate. As a “brewery “ they are a small batch, 5 barrel outfit so that means that they have an extremely limited supply. It takes them 2-4 weeks to brew a new batch supposedly.

Hence, when I went in they had NONE of their beers available and only mostly beers from New Belgium. At $7-8 a beer that’s not their own I could have gone to any other bar for that or a lower price. They didn’t indicate anywhere that these weren’t their own beers except for the small type on their menus inside. It’s basically a crapshoot when you walk in if they have their own brews on tap. Apparently they also serve food as well but I saw nothing below $14 so I hope it’s not small portions.

Given that they are basically the only bar in the area and adjacent to USC ($$$$$) I’m sure they will do well with the frat crowd. I returned with my two friends and had dinner together. I initially thought they only served rice porridge, but there was a wide variety of dishes available. I was pleasantly surprised.

I ordered the mixed seafood and Braised Kimchi, both of which were amazing. I also tried the pumpkin porridge, which I had never had before and found to be delicious.

We thoroughly enjoyed our meal and left the restaurant satisfied. By chance, we met the owner of the restaurant. I complimented a plant on display and she kindly gave it to me as a gift. They don’t use msg and it’s popular with locals for a healthy Korean meal.

When we sat down we got a bunch of seasonal side dishes right away. They were pretty unique, especially the kimchi mushrooms and green seaweed salad. The chive pancake was also really good, packed with flavor and mochi like texture.

We tried the grilled beef patties and LA galbi, they were both great. The beef was tender, grilled just right. Cold noodles were solid, spicy cold noodle were tangy with a nice kick.

The highlight was definitely the abalone beef soup, the abalone always a good size and soaked up the beef broth flavor. The beef itself was incredibly tender and just melted in your mouth.

We got the pumpkin porridge at the end as dessert, it was warm and comforting. All in all, would recommend!', 'languageCode': 'en'}, 'originalText': {'text': 'I recently checked out this spot in Ktown that a friend recommended for its abalone soup. Turkey, Provolone, Roasted Red Peppers, Iceberg, Onion, Oil & Red Wine Vinaigrette.

A couple of things that came to mind. The bread was good, but it was also a bit on the chewy side. Perhaps a slightly too tough for me, but that's me. Turkey was delicious, tender and juicy as expected. I thought I would enjoy the roasted red peppers, but I found they're not for me. I believe this would have been a better sandwich if I stayed away from the roasted red peppers. I didn't like the flavor they brought for me. Other than that, it was a good sandwich. We chose the Large Specialty Set for four, which included beef brisket, pork belly, short rib, seasoned short rib, bulgogi, and an array of delicious side dishes and salads. A standout was the soybean beef brisket ramen at the end—a delightful surprise. The quality of the meats was exceptional, with the pork belly and brisket being particularly outstanding, practically melting in our mouths. The service was impeccable, with our table prepared perfectly before we sat. The exquisite food, attentive service, and captivating ambiance created an unforgettable dining experience. The kale salad was also really good and filling enough to be an entree.  The French toast is a must along with their chilaquiles. Their hummus was also a great try and their egg pizza was so good we got two of them. The indoor bar has a nice welcoming feel too.

The chicken wings were good but only 4 pieces, the bread and tomato sauce dish was also great.  Don’t forget their ice cream also. They had a lot of adult drink options and our server was excellent.

It’s one of the better overall options for quality/price in the LA Live area. It’s become our go-to option before any event we attend in the area, especially when you have a party of people who like different things. Good variety and the food isn’t overly salty like Yardhouse around the corner has become. The food is consistent overall

Cons: Service. While the staff is very friendly. This location seems to be always be understaffed. Service is slow, took us about 5-10 mins after being seated to have the waitress come and address us. Another 5-10 mins to have water brought out. Additionally you have to ask about to have them give you the happy hour menu or else the staff will not mention it. Another thing is asking for accommodations like sauce on the side on things, in the case the ribs. It wasn’t accommodated by the kitchen. I’d easily bump this review up to a 4 stars if it’s improved

The place is nicely decorated and I love the vibes. Although if you sit inside the music can be a bit too loud where you feel like you have to raise your voice to order or have a conversation.

On a better day, I’d want to try sitting on the outdoor patio to eat and people watch.

They may not have a big selection of drinks compared to other venues in the area, but I like their beers. Huckleberry IPA is a unique IPA option they have that I enjoy.

Even though they don’t always listen, I really like the ribs here. Crispy and fall off the bone, put a thin layer of their bbq sauce and it’s great. Umami fries and fried and seasoned well.

HH onion rings and Brussels sprouts are good, portions are small. I do wish there was more brussel sprouts than croutons and capers.

Lettuce wraps are delicious though I wish the cucumbers were pickled more. This time it seemed it was just freshly tossed.

Ahi Tuna bowl- refreshing and light. Easy to pair with other dishes or if you’re not looking for anything heavy

People filled up this spot quickly. Better to reserve a spot!
I enjoyed everything I tasted!
So much flavoring!
Started off with appetizers
Loaded chili cheese totes & crunchy deviled eggs!
I got the black & blu burger with the side of fruit & pb & j cheese burger.

-the Pb & J cheese burger with a side of onion rings.
Pb & j had grape jelly, candied bacon, onions, pickles, & havarti cheese.
Was an interesting Wild Card to try!
You can taste Different flavors one after another  with every bite of this burger.
It's a unique taste.
If you like wild cards, this one's a good experience.

-The Black & blu burger...omg...
So great 👍 👌 👏  damn, the chef was on a role today! Even though it was packed, that burger was So juicy!
The blue cheese hit the spot.
It was tasty I highly recommend it!

*The loaded tots- it came on a small skillet.
I loved the flavors! So delish.
The pickled onions soo good!
Gave it a zesty zing with every bite!
Lots of chili guys.
I am a fan of tots and don't normally favor the chili because it seems to drown out the tots, but woooweeee! That chili's fire!!
It didn't matter to me it was so good I wanted more!

-The crispy deviled eggs...
Wow..was very good. It wouldn't have been my first appetizer on the list but I was so curious. Glad I did.
It had a creamy crispy crunchy with flavor with bacon on top!
Our Waiter was "Rob".
A Very nice gentleman who had lots of recommendations to choose from!
Even though it was a high energy environment and a full house, Rob totally made sure we had everything we needed for dinner.
Thank ya Rob!! Great service doing all you could for everyone around ya!

I enjoyed the time there.

reviews:
[{'name': 'places/ChIJh447PPPHwoARiFsl-R0MpdY/reviews/ChZDSUhNMG9nS0VJQ0FnSUR2Nlp5dEdnEAE', 'relativePublishTimeDescription': '4 months ago', 'rating': 1, 'text': {'text': 'Could not recommend. I placed an order for delivery to treat myself as I remembered liking this place. When my order arrived, I thought I was being punked. It looks nothing like it used to. The bacon was so undercooked, that I believe it is microwaved. The hash brown is simultaneously dry and mushy. The outside is dry and overcooked and the inside is like mashed potatoes. Not to mention flavorless. Not even a grain of salt. It makes me question the freshness of this food.

I can not recommend this place. Unless you can eat in person and send items back.
Overall, save yourself the money and make yourself breakfast at home.', 'languageCode': 'en'}, 'originalText': {'text': 'Could not recommend. I placed an order for delivery to treat myself as I remembered liking this place. When my order arrived, I thought I was being punked. It looks nothing like it used to. The bacon was so undercooked, that I believe it is microwaved. The hash brown is simultaneously dry and mushy. The outside is dry and overcooked and the inside is like mashed potatoes. Plants, lights, good food and good vibes.

You order and the servers bring your food out to you. There is a small wooden table on the inside for four, and lots of seating on the patio.

Wife had the chicken tortilla soup (comes with bread) and a lime-cucumber-chia "agua fresca." I had a grilled chicken lettuce wrap, with grilled chicken breast, roasted red bell pepper and an aioli garlic spread...it was the BOMB.

We had gone there for my daughter to take her SAT, and (making a wrong turn) followed the street down from Woodrow Wilson H.S. It was a surprise.

They close a little early, so check out their website...it would be worth your trip. David was a gracious host, checked on us, and gave a history of the building. Thanks David.

Looking forward to making a wrong turn again and ending up the right place.', 'languageCode': 'en'}, 'originalText': {'text': 'This is a GEM. Plants, lights, good food and good vibes.

You order and the servers bring your food out to you. There is a small wooden table on the inside for four, and lots of seating on the patio.

Wife had the chicken tortilla soup (comes with bread) and a lime-cucumber-chia "agua fresca." I had a grilled chicken lettuce wrap, with grilled chicken breast, roasted red bell pepper and an aioli garlic spread...it was the BOMB.

We had gone there for my daughter to take her SAT, and (making a wrong turn) followed the street down from Woodrow Wilson H.S. It was a surprise.

They close a little early, so check out their website...it would be worth your trip. David was a gracious host, checked on us, and gave a history of the building. Thanks David.

Unfortunately, my visit ended in disappointment, prompting me to share my experience.

Upon entering, I ordered Bistick Tagalog and Pancit Canton. The Bistick Tagalog turned out to be a letdown—boiled beef in an overly salty broth with some cooked onions. To add to my disappointment, the rice portion was only half a cup. After eating half of the Bistick, I called the person behind the counter and asked, "Is this cooked by a Filipino chef?" Initially hesitant, he eventually admitted, "No." I then asked if they had any Filipino chefs, and he replied, "Yeah, we have one chef."

I requested to speak with the Filipino chef. Meanwhile, the counter person offered me a refund if I didn't like the food. I told him to hold off until I spoke to the chef. During this time, I tried the Pancit Canton, which was also disappointing and clearly not cooked by a Filipino chef.

When the Filipino chef arrived, he confirmed that the food was indeed cooked by other chefs who were not Filipino. He was surprised at how I could tell. I explained my background with Filipino cuisine and my love for cooking it. He offered to replace my order, so I requested Laing with rice, insisting it be cooked by the Filipino chef.

When the Laing arrived, it was a relief—it finally felt like I was tasting authentic Filipino food. This dish made me happy and somewhat salvaged my experience at Neri's.

To be fair, the place is very clean, and the staff is friendly. However, the owners need to ensure that the food is consistently authentic. I have been aware of Angela’s because of their other location in East Boston and have always wanted to try it so came to the Orient Heights location on a whim when we were in the area. The staff is really great and warm and welcoming, and the traditional Mexican decor makes it feel homey but the food is reaaaalllly lacking unfortunately. It’s really is not authentic when you compare to food in Mexico which I’ve had the pleasure to have several times. It always isn’t specifically “Puebla” food, it’s pretty run of the mill Mexican dishes from any state of Mexico. The mole poblano is about the most poblano thing on the menu.

When we came in and saw it was empty save for 4 tables of all white families eating (I’m white too so no hate) my first thought “hm…..no Mexicans eating here, will the food be good?” My El Salvadoran husband asked himself the same thing….anyways we were right…the food is VERREEY bland Americanized Mexican food.

We got the guacamole, it was SO overly lemony and lacking salt, and for some reason every other table in the place had salt and pepper on the table except ours and we were to ashamed to ask for one hahaha so that is on us….the chips are clearly fried in house but they were way over cooked and filled with oil and had that slightly burnt taste. The salsas they give with the chips and guacamole really appear to be from a jar but I might be wrong but they are def not Mexican salsas de molcajete.

I got enchiladas Rojas and my husband enchiladas de mole and again everything was so bland, especially the mole which was hugely disappointing as that is supposed to be a hugely flavorful dish from Puebla. The chicken filling was the most bland, flavorless, pulled shredded chicken…we were so surprised.

Anyways being 100% honest we ate it all because it was overall fine, we were starving, it just tasted like nothing…

My recommendations for more authentic flavorful Mexican food in MA:
-Tenoch (multiple locations-Somerville, Medford, Melrose, etc)
-Eloti (multi locations in Revere),
-La Oaxaqueña in Everett and Revere
-and if you ever find yourself in Western MA, La Veracruzana.', 'languageCode': 'en'}, 'originalText': {'text': 'With such a kind staff (5 star) and awesome decor (5 star) I really wanted to love the food here but just couldn’t. Chilacates expanded aggressively throughout the city last year, and this West End location was one of them. Although I haven’t visited their original Amory Street location, this new outpost impressed with its comfortable seatings and a clean, modern interior. I came a couple times before TD garden events and always had a solid meal.

Although Chilacates is more known for their burritos among the locals, I got to try some of their other offerings on the menu. The Taco Plate and Carne Asada Quesadilla, in particular, were some of my favorites. The Birria in the burrito bowl was also soft and tender, but the beans were slightly undercooked, giving them a harder texture than preferred.

From their dessert and drinks, both the churros and the horchata were great. Horchata had a slightly stronger cinnamon flavor compared to what you might find at other taquerias around the city, but it was still refreshing.

With its rapid expansion, Chilacates now rivals chains like Chipotle in number in Boston. If you’re looking for a more authentic Mexican experience, Chilacates is a compelling alternative with its more diversified menu. It may not be the best Mexican food in the city, but it’s good enough to fulfill Mexican food cravings.', 'languageCode': 'en'}, 'originalText': {'text': 'Elevated casual taqueria experience with solid food.

I want to clarify from the start that this review is solely based on my experiences with the live chat agent(s), as well as the website itself.

I say agent(s) because i believe there was only one by the way they spoke (who also stated they were a real person), but I cannot be entirely sure). I started the live chat by stating that their nutrition information and math on their dumplings could not be correct, as they stated one steamed dumpling was 4.1 grams of carbs (take. From liveostrong.com as I later found out), yet somehow said two dumplings would be 12-22 grams of carbs. It doesn't take a mathematician to see this is quite off. Considering there are many with health concerns who may use this highly incorrect information, I decided to let them know of their mistake.

Upon speaking to a live agent and explaining the issue, I was simply given a response of "I apologize", and they asked if they could do anything else. I advised them to make a change for obvious reasons, and they almost instantaneously exited the chat.

I joined a second chat in hopes this would be forwarded to the writer of the article, or website devs  but alas to no avail. Upon reaching them a third time to see what kind of intentions this school really had, they were again extremely indifferent, with their sole and only focus being to get my contact information. Nothing else was even remotely important to them.

For someone who is interested in their school, I highly suggest their actions and false information (and lack thereof to even admit it needs to be changed or forwarded to someone) be taken into careful consideration. From liveostrong.com as I later found out), yet somehow said two dumplings would be 12-22 grams of carbs. It doesn't take a mathematician to see this is quite off. Considering there are many with health concerns who may use this highly incorrect information, I decided to let them know of their mistake.

Upon speaking to a live agent and explaining the issue, I was simply given a response of "I apologize", and they asked if they could do anything else. I advised them to make a change for obvious reasons, and they almost instantaneously exited the chat.

I joined a second chat in hopes this would be forwarded to the writer of the article, or website devs  but alas to no avail. Upon reaching them a third time to see what kind of intentions this school really had, they were again extremely indifferent, with their sole and only focus being to get my contact information. Nothing else was even remotely important to them.

For someone who is interested in their school, I highly suggest their actions and false information (and lack thereof to even admit it needs to be changed or forwarded to someone) be taken into careful consideration. The service is relatively fast, and the food's flavor is absolutely wonderful.

My 3 favorites are the japchae, jp sandwich, and the namesake sandwich. The japchae has a reasonable amount of flavorful (sweet-ish, savory) chicken that will keep you full. The bamboo shoots with the japchae also has a refreshing taste. The JP sandwich has plenty of tasty tofu inside (no meat, but filling; bought it 4 times), and the namesake, which I've only tried once, became my new favorite from Bon Me as well. The namesake's tasty pulled pork with the slightly sweet/tangy sauce makes it a really good lunch. These sandwich's sizes are also relatively large for a great price ($11-$12).  The sandwich bread also has a satisfying crunch to it (obviously unless the sauce inside infiltrates it).

The taste may not be of 'traditional Korean/Singaporean/Vietnamese' taste, but this is an Asian fusion restaurant, meaning unique cooking from different parts of Asia are combined. This place should satisfy your Asian food cravings, as the food here isn't too "Americanized". Also, the staff was very friendly and efficient! I felt comfortable ordering from them. The other reviews say they appear rude, but I think that's due to efficiently working throughout the whole day. Our server even brought a little cut of warm butter, that added as needed (some places drench the entire sandwich in butter and ends up falling apart in your hands). Every detail here feels intentional, from the efficiency and warmth of the staff to the artistry of each dish.

The star of the show? Their pork and crab soup dumplings — hands down the best I’ve ever tasted. The moment you bite into that delicate, perfectly pleated dumpling, you’re met with an explosion of rich, flavorful broth that feels almost too luxurious to be real. The balance of sweet crab, savory pork, and aromatic soup is pure magic — a flavor that lingers and leaves you dreaming about your next visit.

Nan Xiang Express doesn’t just serve food; they deliver an experience, one beautiful dumpling at a time. If you think you know good soup dumplings, think again — this is the gold standard.', 'languageCode': 'en'}, 'originalText': {'text': 'Nan Xiang Express is an absolute gem — a masterclass in how exceptional food and service can turn a quick meal into a memory you crave again and again. Every detail here feels intentional, from the efficiency and warmth of the staff to the artistry of each dish.

The star of the show? Their pork and crab soup dumplings — hands down the best I’ve ever tasted. The moment you bite into that delicate, perfectly pleated dumpling, you’re met with an explosion of rich, flavorful broth that feels almost too luxurious to be real. Ordering is a cinch as well. You can either order at the counter or if you're not feeling very sociable you can order at the touch screen. If you're eating in you can grab a number, enter it with your order and they'll bring it out to you!

Items we ordered (as of 9/2024)

- Crab meat and pork soup dumplings - $9.95 - The meat filling was pretty good and there was a decent amount of broth! Overall it wasn't bad although the dumpling skin itself was a bit mushy. Overall I'd try the regular pork soup dumplings next time.

-Pork Crispy Bottom Buns (4pc) - $7.95 - The buns were alright. The meat filling was decent but the buns (like the soup dumplings) had a bit of a mushy aftertaste to it. Not sure if it was just the batch they used for us but it wasn't as fluffy as I'd expect. I'd pass on this one in the future.

- Shredded Beef & Pepper Noodles (Dry) - $14.95 - Great spicy flavor. The meat and veggies are good although the noodles were a bit overcooked.

- Cucumber Salad w. Garlic Vinaigrette (Cold) - $7.95 - We really enjoyed this dish as the cucumbers were fresh and crisp. The garlic vinaigrette was great and overall a very good palate cleanser. Good quantity as well.

- Crispy Sesame Chicken Bowl - $13.95 - Overall this dish is alright. The chicken was tender and crispy but the Sesame sauce was lacking. I'd probably pass on this in the future.

- Beef Scallion Pancake (3pcs) - $8.95 - This was probably my favorite dish of the night. The scallion pancake was VERY crispy and tasty and the hoisin sauce and beef was perfect ratio-wise. I'd get this one again in a heartbeat.

Overall I'm happy to have a decent soup dumpling place in the South End and look forward to coming back to try their other offerings! I'm hoping that the bun and dumpling skin mushiness was a one-off moment but we'll have to just wait and see next time.", 'languageCode': 'en'}, 'originalText': {'text': "Great ambiance at this location and very spacious! The line can be daunting but the staff work hard to keep it flowing and delivery high quality food and drinks! I doubt I’ll ever be disappointed on any future visits.

Food: The drinks were very refreshing and a great wake up jolt of caffeine. I was intrigued by the espresso soda and I was not disappointed. It was such a nice blend of fruity flavors that slide perfectly into a familiar coffee taste. The sweet ricotta toast and the egg cheddar sandwich were amazing! The sourdough and ciabatta were the stars and their great bready textures made for perfect vehicles.

Service: The staff worked like a well oiled machine but still offered great hospitality!

Atmosphere: The popularity does cause the cafe to be busy but everyone was very respectful of one another’s space so it wasn’t an overwhelming crowd. The decorations also added to the energetic atmosphere.', 'languageCode': 'en'}, 'originalText': {'text': 'Absolutely deserving of the Best Cafe in Somerville title! [{'name': 'places/ChIJTb0HOgBx44kRTSjWfeGKF8E/reviews/ChZDSUhNMG9nS0VJQ0FnTUNveTlmUUpBEAE', 'relativePublishTimeDescription': '3 weeks ago', 'rating': 4, 'text': {'text': 'We tried the Chop Cheese Rice Cake and the Legendary Cheese Burger—both were fairly good. As a Korean, I was curious to see how well this place fused Korean and American flavors. I enjoyed the crunch of the garlic on the rice cake and appreciated the mild, milky flavor that wasn’t too spicy.

The cheeseburger came on a nice buttery bun with well-seasoned meat and good cheese, but I was hoping for more kimchi. It mostly just tasted like a regular cheeseburger, which was a bit of a letdown.

At $26, the burger wasn’t cheap, but considering the quality of the furniture (just look at the legs of those wooden chairs), the price didn’t feel too unreasonable. The atmosphere was lively, and I liked the Korean-inspired decor. That said, I wish there was more thought put into the music—it seemed like the owner is a fan of ’90s rap, which didn’t quite match the vibe. I even overheard people at another table commenting on it.

For my non-alcoholic drink, I had the “Respect Your Elders,” which had a nice yuzu flavor I really enjoyed.

Overall, a decent spot—some hits, some misses, but worth a try.', 'languageCode': 'en'}, 'originalText': {'text': 'We tried the Chop Cheese Rice Cake and the Legendary Cheese Burger—both were fairly good. Stopped by for dinner during their opening week. In NY, Nowon earned a lot of love for its smash burgers, and the Korean influences made it sound even more enticing.

At first, though, nothing about the vibe felt particularly Korean. More of a Hong Kong bar feel—red neon lights, dark and loud—aesthetic more in line with Seaport Asian fusion spots like Empire or Mr. H than anything uniquely Korean.

The menu had some tweaks from their NY locations. One thing that stood out was the “Mixtape” option—a tasting menu (for two or more) that lets you try a couple of their most popular dishes. We opted for the basic E.P. Mixtape, which came with five plates. Fun concept, but it leaned a little carb-heavy by the end.

The first two dishes were just fine. Black Sesame caesar salad barely registered any black sesame at all. Mostly just a standard caesar with extra-crunchy garlic panko. General Lee’s chicken was probably the biggest miss. It was mostly breast meat—dry, stringy, over-fried. The honey-gochujang glaze came thick, sticky, and almost syrupy. Couldn’t tell what separated this from a generic General Tso’s other than the name.

Thankfully, the last three plates were great. Chopped Cheese rice cakes were slightly crisped on the edges with a chewy core, like a pan-fried tteok. The sauce had real character: beefy, tangy, with just a touch of heat from jalapeño. Gave off rosé tteokbokki(Korean-Italian fusion) vibes.

Honey Garlic Butter Tots were unexpectedly nostalgic (for me). The garlic-butter base was solid, but it was the seaweed and sesame dusting that made them addictive—crispy, salty-sweet, umami-rich (almost like a Kim bugak).

The Legendary Burger was a great smash burger. Good char, well-toasted bun, not overly greasy. However, I expected bolder acidity or kimchi-forward flavors, and got only the faintest hint—maybe one diluted piece in the half of the burger.

Maybe a good stop for burgers, tots, and rice cakes, but otherwise, I wouldn’t come back.', 'languageCode': 'en'}, 'originalText': {'text': 'Not sure what it is about Seaport’s Asian fusion spots, but even this NYC transplant was a tad disappointing.

Today was disappointing My friend uses a wheelchair, and when we arrived, the floor manager informed us that the earliest available reservation would be at 9 PM. Two customers arrived after us and were given the same information, but we noticed that they were seated after only about six minutes of waiting. I approached the manager to ask if the wait time had improved, but he didn’t directly answer. Instead, he told us the wait would now be 45 minutes due to a last-minute cancellation. He also mentioned that there was only one wheelchair-accessible table available for my friend.

If a wheelchair-accessible table wasn’t available, we would have been happy to be seated at a regular table instead. It is SUPER tiny inside, and yet lots of people were busy working, so it’s a popular place!

The pastries and cookies look phenomenal but I didn’t try.  They have MEM tea, and this matcha is very genuine Japanese matcha.  It tastes phenomenal.

I love that they also have Peaflower lemonade and 10% discounts for those who bike in.

There is parking right out front, and there is only one step to enter, BUT that one step is unusually high up.  If you have trouble with steps, this might be a challenge for you.

The cocktails were well-crafted and refreshing, though our server seemed unaware that Tajin was available for the spicy margarita, which was a bit disappointing.

The food, however, didn’t quite hit the mark for us. As a fusion Indian-American restaurant, we expected bold, vibrant flavors, but the dishes lacked the punch and spice we were hoping for. The Kerala fried chicken, for instance, was dry and less flavorful compared to the Nashville fried chicken you’d find at local Boston pubs. The avocado toast, which mentioned green chutney, came with only a hint of red crust and didn’t deliver on the promised flavor profile.

While the concept is interesting, the execution needs improvement to truly stand out. With some tweaks to the spice levels and flavor balance, Rosebud could be a much stronger contender. We kicked things off with the vegan ravioli—absolutely delicious and full of rich, savory flavor. It’s a must-try for anyone, vegan or not. Then came the La Vegetariana pizza, loaded with fresh, colorful veggies on a perfectly crisp, wood-fired crust. We also ordered the gnocchi di patate and classic Olio e Aglio pasta, which were both flawless—the gnocchi was soft and pillowy, while the pasta was simple, garlicky, and packed with bold, comforting flavor. The sautéed broccoli rabe added a nice bitter bite that balanced everything out. To top it all off, we sipped on a refreshing virgin mojito and finished with creamy chocolate and vanilla ice cream. Every dish felt fresh, homemade, and made with love. Whether you’re plant-based or just love good Italian food, Antico Forno is a must-visit!

reviewSummary: {'text': {'text': 'Diners say this southern Italian restaurant serves up delicious brick oven pizza, including the margherita pizza, and fresh pasta dishes, such as the rigatoni alla boscaiola. For appetizers, we had the beetroot croquettes and kale chaat — both were excellent. In the main course, we ordered tandoori and garlic naan paired with paneer pasinda and jackfruit kofta curry. The jackfruit kofta curry was just okay, not as impressive as the rest, but overall, the food was really good.

The restaurant space was quite small, and the tables for two felt a bit cramped. Price-wise, it was reasonable. The menu strikes a good balance—comprehensive without being overwhelming, allowing you to explore authentic flavors without decision fatigue.

The Ssaanjh special butter chicken was a highlight, featuring generous chunks of tender chicken in a rich, flavorful sauce. Their paneer pasanda had a delightfully mellow profile that complemented the other dishes nicely. The vegetable biryani was slightly dry, though this might have been due to our request for mild spicing.

While the culinary execution was nearly flawless, the service unfortunately didn't match the same standard. The initial greeting lacked warmth, and despite no visible waiting party, we felt rushed to leave at the 1.5-hour mark.

Overall, Ssaanjh delivers outstanding food in a refined setting. It’s incomparable to British Indian restaurants, but pretty decent for the Boston restaurant scene.", 'languageCode': 'en'}, 'originalText': {'text': "Ssaanjh offers an elevated Indian dining experience with exceptional food quality and presentation. We started with the beetroot peanut croquette and kale sakarandi chaat—both appetizers were bursting with flavor and beautifully presented. For mains, the paneer pasanda was out of this world—rich, creamy, and layered with flavor. It paired perfectly with the comforting daal makhani.

The garlic naan and butter naan were hot, fluffy, and ideal for scooping up every last bit of sauce. And for dessert, the shahi waffle was spot-on—creative, balanced, and the perfect sweet finish.

The vibes were amazing—warm, modern, and inviting. Whether you’re planning a special date night or just a regular dinner with friends, this place fits the bill perfectly.

Special shoutout to owner Manju, who was absolutely sweet and went above and beyond to make sure we had a wonderful experience. Her warmth and care made the night even more memorable.

Highly recommend Saanjh for anyone looking for thoughtful, elevated Indian cuisine.', 'languageCode': 'en'}, 'originalText': {'text': 'Saanjh is a culinary gem in Brookline!

They have a downstairs section that is cozy but still in the works that is great for privacy, and it's wonderful their open late for a chill evening get together when you feel more like tea and less like mixed drinks.

The best meal they have is in the picture, and I think it's called Ciro Hawawshi. It's seasoned beef in fried pita with fresh and pickled vegetables. Healthy and delicious for breakfast or anytime. Although, currently only available as a weekend special.

Their French toasts, coffees, and sweets are phenomenal as well. The one place I think they have for improvement are their sandwiches. They're fine, but I'd recommend getting something more traditionally Egyptian when it comes to their food, as that is where they excel. I'd love to see them offering more authentic or fusion regional dishes as they continue.

reviews:
[{'name': 'places/ChIJIQrO4ulw44kRNccHYQ2xjNk/reviews/ChZDSUhNMG9nS0VJQ0FnTURJLVA3NFFREAE', 'relativePublishTimeDescription': 'a month ago', 'rating': 3, 'text': {'text': "The atmosphere was beautiful, and there was a second area as well beyond the wall. The staff was overall nice, but our waiter at times felt as if he had forgotten about us.
For the food, the highlights for me were the salmon roll and the mango pudding. The crab ragoon had more cream cheese than crab, although good I expect more crab meat when ordering at a restaurant. The grilled chicken teriyaki was a pass altogether. Now I love me some dumplings and gyoza were stuffed just like I like em' but again I felt like I had better. The house fried rice came with a side sauce that resembles a cheese sauce, but the sauce to add that made took it up a notch was the chili sauce that came with the crab rangoon. The salmon roll needed nothing, not even soy sauce. The balance of flavors and the sauce placed on top was the perfect combination! I am normally not a pudding person, but the mango pudding was amazing!!! Light, refreshing, and flavorful, we cleared the bowl.
The yuzu martini was a refreshing citrus flavor with a kick. The maitai was the right amount of sweet with a good balance of rum.", 'languageCode': 'en'}, 'originalText': {'text': "The atmosphere was beautiful, and there was a second area as well beyond the wall. The grilled chicken teriyaki was a pass altogether. Now I love me some dumplings and gyoza were stuffed just like I like em' but again I felt like I had better. The house fried rice came with a side sauce that resembles a cheese sauce, but the sauce to add that made took it up a notch was the chili sauce that came with the crab rangoon. The salmon roll needed nothing, not even soy sauce. The balance of flavors and the sauce placed on top was the perfect combination! There are two separate bars in different rooms, each with its own unique vibe, making it a great spot to explore and find the perfect setting for your night. It really added to the overall atmosphere.

From the hosts to the waiters to the managers and bartenders, everyone was wonderful. The staff was attentive, friendly, and quick to assist. They made sure we had everything we needed without being overwhelming, which was much appreciated.

Convenient parking was available with a garage nearby. The first two hours are free, which is a nice perk. Plus, the restaurant is conveniently located next to Urban Wild, adding to the overall vibe of the area.

Unfortunately, the food didn’t live up to expectations, and considering the prices, it really didn’t feel worth it. The fusion dishes didn’t hit for us, lacking the flavor profile I was hoping for, and the overall quality didn’t justify the cost.

On the other hand, the drinks were wonderful. Creative and refreshing, they were definitely a highlight of the meal.  We liked everything we tried from the sake, to the martinis, mojitos, and margaritas.

A downside in IMO was the use of a palm pilot for payment. I’m not a fan of this method, so I asked for the bill to be printed out so I could review the charges. It feels awkward for the waiter to stand there while we try to scroll through to review charges on the device and then make payment and tip while they are watching.

As a sweet touch, they surprised us with fresh chocolate-dipped strawberries at the end of our meal, which was a lovely gesture for the occasion.  We also got fortune cookies.

While the food may not be worth the prices, this place is perfect for a date night, especially if you’re just looking for a great spot to enjoy drinks at the bar and a light bite. There are two separate bars that give you some great options, and the environment and cocktails make it a fun and relaxed outing. Came here for an early dinner this past week. Aside from Nautilus, I haven’t found a spot in Boston that really nails Asian fusion, and unfortunately, Lucky Tiger was no exception. We shared five dishes, and while the portions were decent, the food lacked the kind of balance and complexity I usually expect from good Asian fusion.

Favorites: Sweet & Sticky Spare ribs
Solid: Spicy Tuna Roll, Chef’s House Fried Rice
Poor: Pork Gyoza Dumplings, Udon Noodles

The Spare Ribs was the best dish of the night — light, crispy skin with exceptionally tender meat inside. The sweet and spicy hoisin sauce was just okay, but honestly, the ribs didn’t even need it. The Fried Rice was probably the most flavorful item we tried. Not amazing, but still better than everything else we ordered. The Tuna Rolls were solid — nothing mind-blowing, but decent for the price.

The udon noodles and the dumplings were pretty bad. The dumplings had thick skin, small filling, and were just bland — frankly worse than low-tier HMart frozen dumplings. The udon noodles were undercooked, and the lone fried egg didn’t do much to balanced the overly acidic sauce. My biggest issue with these was the overall lack of layered flavors. They seemed to rely too heavily on tanginess without much complexity. I love acidity in fusion dishes when it's paired with sweetness or spice, but here, it just felt uninspired and monotonous.

Service didn’t help either. Despite the restaurant being nearly empty, our server was practically missing the entire meal.

Overall, a few decent bites, but not enough to make me want to come back. Not sure how long this place is going to last, but I’d be surprised if it sticks around longer than the Mexican spot that was here before.", 'languageCode': 'en'}, 'originalText': {'text': "Another Asian fusion spot without the flair.

Favorites: Sweet & Sticky Spare ribs
Solid: Spicy Tuna Roll, Chef’s House Fried Rice
Poor: Pork Gyoza Dumplings, Udon Noodles

The Spare Ribs was the best dish of the night — light, crispy skin with exceptionally tender meat inside. The sweet and spicy hoisin sauce was just okay, but honestly, the ribs didn’t even need it. The Fried Rice was probably the most flavorful item we tried. Not amazing, but still better than everything else we ordered. The Tuna Rolls were solid — nothing mind-blowing, but decent for the price.

The udon noodles and the dumplings were pretty bad. The dumplings had thick skin, small filling, and were just bland — frankly worse than low-tier HMart frozen dumplings. The udon noodles were undercooked, and the lone fried egg didn’t do much to balanced the overly acidic sauce. My biggest issue with these was the overall lack of layered flavors. They seemed to rely too heavily on tanginess without much complexity. I love acidity in fusion dishes when it's paired with sweetness or spice, but here, it just felt uninspired and monotonous.

Service didn’t help either. Despite the restaurant being nearly empty, our server was practically missing the entire meal.

Overall, a few decent bites, but not enough to make me want to come back. Not sure how long this place is going to last, but I’d be surprised if it sticks around longer than the Mexican spot that was here before.", 'languageCode': 'en'}, 'authorAttribution': {'displayName': 'Jea Kim', 'uri': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/117730837401207768949/reviews', 'photoUri': 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/ALV-UjWwKV1KDmKWV1nfFpDkm8UJG2u1w2QEXIRnFg5lfgWSH3TlXdzMoQ=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo-ba7'}, 'publishTime': '2025-03-08T07:00:54.848096Z', 'flagContentUri': 'https://www.google.com/local/review/rap/report?postId=ChdDSUhNMG9nS0VJQ0FnTUNRMzQyRHRnRRAB&d=17924085&t=1', 'googleMapsUri': 'https://www.google.com/maps/reviews/data=!4m6!14m5!1m4!2m3!1sChdDSUhNMG9nS0VJQ0FnTUNRMzQyRHRnRRAB!2m1!1s0x89e370e9e2ce0a21:0xd98cb10d6107c735'}, {'name': 'places/ChIJIQrO4ulw44kRNccHYQ2xjNk/reviews/ChdDSUhNMG9nS0VJQ0FnSUNmaHBmaW1BRRAB', 'relativePublishTimeDescription': '4 months ago', 'rating': 5, 'text': {'text': "This place has the best customer service, food, and great atmosphere! To be fair, we were informed ahead of time that the restaurant would be hosting an event later that evening, so the slightly rushed pace of the meal wasn’t entirely unexpected. Still, it did make it hard to settle in and fully enjoy what was meant to be a relaxed, celebratory dinner.

Several dishes missed the mark, especially given the price point. The wagyu steak, which we had high hopes for, lacked the tenderness and richness we anticipated, it came across as rather plain. The foie gras special also didn’t quite justify its cost, and the escargot had a flavor that felt off. On the other hand, the bone marrow appetizer was delicious and the standout of the evening. The salmon crudo and razor clam ceviche were okay but didn’t particularly impress, and while the duck and wagyu steak were fine, they weren’t especially memorable. The surprising star of the dinner was the roasted half chicken with crispy skin and moist meat that were perfectly executed.

I also have to mention the bread roll served at the beginning of the meal as it was warm, soft, and absolutely delightful. I wish the rest of the courses had maintained that level of comfort and satisfaction.

Ultimately, I left feeling a bit disappointed, especially given that we chose Troquet over three other options for such meaningful celebrations. That said, I recognize the unique circumstances of the evening, and I’m open to returning, perhaps to try their multi-course tasting menu at a more leisurely pace.

For now, I would give Troquet a 3 out of 5 stars, with genuine hope that a future visit will offer the kind of experience I know they’re capable of delivering!', 'languageCode': 'en'}, 'originalText': {'text': 'We recently dined at Troquet for a special evening of milestone celebrations, and while I truly wanted to love the experience, it unfortunately fell short of expectations.

To be fair, we were informed ahead of time that the restaurant would be hosting an event later that evening, so the slightly rushed pace of the meal wasn’t entirely unexpected. Still, it did make it hard to settle in and fully enjoy what was meant to be a relaxed, celebratory dinner.

Several dishes missed the mark, especially given the price point. The wagyu steak, which we had high hopes for, lacked the tenderness and richness we anticipated, it came across as rather plain. The foie gras special also didn’t quite justify its cost, and the escargot had a flavor that felt off. On the other hand, the bone marrow appetizer was delicious and the standout of the evening. The salmon crudo and razor clam ceviche were okay but didn’t particularly impress, and while the duck and wagyu steak were fine, they weren’t especially memorable. The surprising star of the dinner was the roasted half chicken with crispy skin and moist meat that were perfectly executed.

I also have to mention the bread roll served at the beginning of the meal as it was warm, soft, and absolutely delightful. I wish the rest of the courses had maintained that level of comfort and satisfaction.

Ultimately, I left feeling a bit disappointed, especially given that we chose Troquet over three other options for such meaningful celebrations. That said, I recognize the unique circumstances of the evening, and I’m open to returning, perhaps to try their multi-course tasting menu at a more leisurely pace.

For now, I would give Troquet a 3 out of 5 stars, with genuine hope that a future visit will offer the kind of experience I know they’re capable of delivering!', 'languageCode': 'en'}, 'authorAttribution': {'displayName': 'Teavy Leonardson', 'uri': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/108028092828186021592/reviews', 'photoUri': 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a/ACg8ocJbXWp_KKoXJO7S3Q1zkV1XxLS2taQiVF_gFjPa9s-pVoanFQ=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo'}, 'publishTime': '2025-04-20T03:06:54.004294Z', 'flagContentUri': 'https://www.google.com/local/review/rap/report?postId=ChZDSUhNMG9nS0VJQ0FnTUNvNjlPWFd3EAE&d=17924085&t=1', 'googleMapsUri': 'https://www.google.com/maps/reviews/data=!4m6!14m5!1m4!2m3!1sChZDSUhNMG9nS0VJQ0FnTUNvNjlPWFd3EAE!2m1!1s0x89e37a766a38a351:0x405238ff2166f92e'}, {'name': 'places/ChIJUaM4anZ644kRLvlmIf84UkA/reviews/ChZDSUhNMG9nS0VJQ0FnTUNZbXFHLUd3EAE', 'relativePublishTimeDescription': 'a week ago', 'rating': 4, 'text': {'text': 'Loved the setting and our main courses of the veal chop and sirloin were great but.. we ordered the 6 Oysters app and what a let down. From the moment I entered the hotel, I was warmly greeted by staff—such a pleasant surprise compared to my recent experience at the Mandarin Oriental in Boston. A helpful employee directed me to the correct elevator and wished me a good evening as I headed up to Amar.

The restaurant’s staff were equally lovely. I interacted with about four different servers, all of whom were attentive and gracious. Eugene, in particular, stood out for his professionalism and warmth.

I ordered from the à la carte menu, starting with the baby gem salad and King crab appetizer—both beautifully prepared and delicious. For entrées, I had the halibut and the lamb, which were equally impressive. I finished with a delicate rhubarb and elderflower dessert and a refreshing shaved ice—a light and creative end to a memorable meal.

The ambiance is polished yet welcoming, with gorgeous views from the 17th floor. Between the setting, the service, and the cuisine, Amar is a standout in Boston’s fine dining scene. I would happily return.

What’s nice is when I went back to the hotel lobby, I asked the reception if it was OK for me to sit down while I called a rideshare, and a response was of course. So different from the response I received from the general manager at the Mandarin Oriental in Boston. reviews:
[{'name': 'places/ChIJ3-SVZWN544kRQjvOswvK18o/reviews/ChdDSUhNMG9nS0VJQ0FnTURvcE5xVm1BRRAB', 'relativePublishTimeDescription': '3 weeks ago', 'rating': 5, 'text': {'text': 'One of the holes in the wall, turn around the corner from the main street, lookout for their advertisement board to go down basement level.

We were greeted with friendly welcomes and seated quickly. Not a big menu but that’s how you know they’re Hokkaido specialty only. Service was quick and the place is clean.

Got the shoyu ramen and spicy miso ramen, both broth were rich and heavy as to Hokkaido style. You can taste the umami of mushroom in the shoyu, which makes every bite of noodles enjoyable. However, the spicy miso isn’t actually spicy. Tasted more peppery than your usual spicy ramen, it was unexpected. Hokkaido ramen doesn’t have egg, but you can add-on for $2. Overall, this ramen style is bold, heavy (fatty), and rich. Overall, the food was very good, though pricier than most other ramen places in the area. The egg was extra on the ramen and the portions are smaller than Ganko's ramen half a block away. Staff was kind and attentive, and the atmosphere was somehow homey and refined at the same time.

We had the Zangi Chicken, a kaarage type chicken with a nice citrus sauce, and both the Toasted Sesame and Shoyu Ramen (with an egg of course!) Both were absolutely fantastic. I preferred the shoyu broth, but the sesame miso had the nice touch of being able to grind and add your own sesame seeds to add a creamy/nutty flavor.

A more than worthy addition to the already impressive ramen selection in Coolidge!', 'languageCode': 'en'}, 'originalText': {'text': 'A small but modern ramen shop tucked away in an alleyway off of Coolidge Corner, this new ramen shop made the nearly hour wait absolutely worth it.

Started with a light yet slightly flavored Japanese beer that had a hint of acidity and a lovely touch of citrus at every sip. Perfect for every occasion at this establishment.

Next we got the Chashu Don and the Zangi Fried Chicken.

The Chashu Don was chopped up and laid onto a soft bed of white rice and sweet yet savory sauce. With a small portion of vegetables and laying on-top the dish waiting to be mixed all around and having a bit of all portions in one spoonful. With all this comes a soft boiled egg to clean your pallet.

Next we tried the Zangi Fried Chicken, 4 to 5 pieces of fried to perfection chicken, lightly battered and a savory yet dressing drizzled onto the dish. This chicken had the juices falling out of it practically asking to be drank out of the portions like you didn’t want to lose any of the deliciously seasoned portions. This has to be ordered every time you go here.

Now comes hands down some of the best ramen I’ve yet to taste. The broth, soft with flavors of a Kombu and Miso to give you a smack of delight to run across your tongue. The oil and fat tasted is this dish is by far one of the most perfected amount every deemed necessary and I wouldn’t ask for my broth to be anything other then this. The thinly sliced portions of Chashu pork, a light as well as spicy chili paste to mix all portions of this dish to a taste of perfection. The noodles have such an amazing bounce and chew to them. It’s a texture that almost seems impossible to perfect yet the chefs have. The flavors all come together in unison. This will always be a recommendation by me for any and all patrons that want to come here.

And finally comes the dessert.

A soft and lightly sweetened Hojicha Chiffron Cake. This cake was absolutely necessary to end the meal off on a better high note than I would ever expect it to be. A soft and light cake that seemed as though you were hurting it by trying to cut out portions with a fork, as well as the single scoop of vanilla ice cream they all with whipped cream and a cherry decadently placed practically hiding in plain sight. This cake had some of the best flavor and bite I’ve had from anywhere else.

To all patrons that want to come here and enjoy a nice meal with a friend or even alone I would strongly encourage them to eat at this location.', 'languageCode': 'en'}, 'originalText': {'text': 'First time walking in, greeted warmly by the staff of the establishment, short wait time and able to sit at the counter to start my ordering process.

Even mediocre spots like Brooklyn Bagel Factory had long lines when they first opened. However, during my past few visits to Rebelle, I didn’t see any lines. This Providence transplant hasn’t gained a good reputation among the locals, and the owner's unpopularity on social media and online forums seemed to be the biggest factor.

At Rebelle, owner Milena is strict about how to enjoy her bagels—R&D only, no toasting. She's quite adamant about preserving the air pockets in her freshly-baked bagels, which theoretically gives them a better texture and density. While I respect her dedication to bagel perfection, I have to admit, I prefer to enjoy them in sandwich form for convenience. Sometimes, you just need a bagel that’s more grab-and-go.

During my past few visits, I usually arrived around opening time, and there was always a limited selection of bagels—typically just 3-4 options, with flavors varying by the day. Some of my favorite sandwiches and combos included the pretzel bagel with Honey Fleur de Sel cream cheese, the Lox sandwich, and the BLT Squared sandwich. The bagels here are on the smaller side, but they still have a satisfying chewiness and density. However, because of their size, one sandwich usually isn’t enough to fill me up, which makes me question if it’s worth the price.

Really hoped that Rebelle would become my reliable go-to spot for bagel sandwiches in Cambridge. Their sandwiches are good, but perhaps not the best value. Might return to try their smoked fish sandwiches, but for now, I’ll likely look elsewhere to satisfy my bagel cravings.", 'languageCode': 'en'}, 'originalText': {'text': "When bagel shops first open in Boston and Cambridge, they usually attract a lot of hype. Even mediocre spots like Brooklyn Bagel Factory had long lines when they first opened. However, during my past few visits to Rebelle, I didn’t see any lines. This Providence transplant hasn’t gained a good reputation among the locals, and the owner's unpopularity on social media and online forums seemed to be the biggest factor.

At Rebelle, owner Milena is strict about how to enjoy her bagels—R&D only, no toasting. She's quite adamant about preserving the air pockets in her freshly-baked bagels, which theoretically gives them a better texture and density. While I respect her dedication to bagel perfection, I have to admit, I prefer to enjoy them in sandwich form for convenience. Sometimes, you just need a bagel that’s more grab-and-go.

During my past few visits, I usually arrived around opening time, and there was always a limited selection of bagels—typically just 3-4 options, with flavors varying by the day. Some of my favorite sandwiches and combos included the pretzel bagel with Honey Fleur de Sel cream cheese, the Lox sandwich, and the BLT Squared sandwich. The bagels here are on the smaller side, but they still have a satisfying chewiness and density. However, because of their size, one sandwich usually isn’t enough to fill me up, which makes me question if it’s worth the price.

Really hoped that Rebelle would become my reliable go-to spot for bagel sandwiches in Cambridge. Their sandwiches are good, but perhaps not the best value. We booked in advance, anticipating a set menu that was not cheap but promised a luxurious dining experience. Upon arrival, the ambiance was undeniably beautiful, with an elegant setting that matched the festive occasion.

Our evening started on a disappointing note when we were informed that they had run out of caviar for the burrata dish we ordered. Although they offered a truffle alternative, it didn’t quite hit the mark for us, especially considering the expectations set by the menu’s description. This minor setback was compounded by the uncomfortably cold temperature in the dining area, which forced us to dine in our coats, somewhat diminishing the elegance of the evening.

The wine selection was impressive, offering a wide variety that catered to diverse palates. However, the overall value for the price we paid didn’t seem justifiable, especially with the compromises we had to make, such as eating under a large, awkwardly placed planter that added to our discomfort.

The highlight of the evening was undoubtedly the DJ, who provided an excellent soundtrack that truly captured the spirit of New Year’s Eve. The music and the lively atmosphere he created were the saving graces of our celebration.

Despite the beautiful decor and the festive ambiance, the combination of service missteps, seating discomfort, and the chill in the dining room led us to decide not to recommend Contessa for future New Year’s Eve celebrations. Food: We got the beef chow fun and also the Mac and cheese with milk tea and also the tofu. I thought that the food was quite standard Chinese food and nothing too special. Wouldn’t recommend the Mac and cheese special though.

Service: The waiters were extremely kind and helpful! I was surprised, maybe because we were one of the few customers there. Food also came super quickly!

Ambiance: Very causal. It’s a little bit dirty inside.

The food? Phenomenal.
Albondigas, some of the best meatballs we’ve had recently, the citrus element was different, made it refreshing.
Escalivadas were creamy, full flavor, and the crispy thin focaccia was a great contrast.
Choripan was one of my favorite chorizo recipes of recent as well, being well paired with the garlic aioli and salsa verde.
The lamb in the Pintxos Morunos was so tender and so great.
Fideua Mar y Montana was the star of the show, and was an amazing squid ink dish. Stuffed Squid with chorizo was a great touch.
Finished with olive oil cake, Tarta De Naranja, which was also amazing and a great compliment to a great meal.

Lastly ONLY on Sunday during brunch did I get to try their yogurt bowl in their special menu that’s only available on that day of the week and that time. Yogurt was good but the flavor is VERY sharp so it may not be for everyone.
